@Section
@Title { Ecuación de Schrodinger independiente del tiempo}
@Begin
@DP
Resulta sencillo obtener la ecuación de Schrodinger a partir de la relación anterior. En efecto, si consideramos :
@DP
@Math {nabla  sup {2} Psi  -   {2m sub {0}c } over {hbar } blpar {E sub {m}} over {hbar c} - {alpha} over {r} brpar Psi  - blpar {alpha sup {2} } over {r sup {2} } brpar Psi = 0}
@DP
y despreciando el término  @Math {alpha sup {2}  over {r sup {2} }} frente a @Math {{alpha} over {r}}
@DP 
@Math {nabla sup {2}  Psi  +  {2m sub {0} c} over {hbar} blpar E over {hbar c} - {alpha } over {r} brpar Psi  =      0  }
 @DP 
 o, lo que es lo mismo
 @DP
 @Math {  {hbar} over {2m sub {0} c}   nabla sup {2}  Psi  +   blpar E over {hbar c} - {alpha } over {r} brpar Psi  =      0  }
 @DP
y recordando que:
@DP
@Math {alpha={e sup {2}} over {hbar c 4 pi  epsilon sub {0}}} @DP
@DP 
Nos queda:
@DP
@Math {  {hbar} over {2m sub {0} c}   nabla sup {2}  Psi  +   blpar E over {hbar c} - {e sup {2} } over {4 pi epsilon sub {0} hbar c r} brpar Psi  =      0  }
@DP 
Multiplicando por @Math {hbar c} y reordenando:
@DP

@Math {  {hbar sup {2}} over {2m sub {0} }   nabla sup {2}  Psi  +   blpar E  - {e sup {2} } over {4 pi epsilon sub {0}  r} brpar Psi  =      0  }         @Sym arrowright       @Box   @Math {       blpar {- hbar sup {2}} over {2m sub {0} }  + {e sup {2} } over {4 pi epsilon sub {0}  r} brpar Psi  =       E  nabla sup {2}  Psi  }



   

@End @Section
